Radio America, the fledgling Washington-based radio network that supplies 170 local stations around the country with rock-ribbed cassette messages from such conservative spokesmen as Jack F. Kemp, M. Stanton Evans and Orrin G. Hatch, is appealing for funds to ''get through the next three months.'' Senator Steven D. Symms of Idaho says in a fund-raising letter that the service is needed because ''the overwhelming majority of journalists consider themselves liberals, and their coverage of the news often reflects that bias.''